choices.text:
by bike. I’m talking a sprint to the grocery store, bike the 1km stretch, BACK to the house, full speed (almost), as long at the grocery bags stay on the bike. When I put them in the cart thingy it didn’t go so well 😛 That wasn’t as much an emphasis as the environmental use of the bike, just that it was a way to get fresh air, out in the sun (no sunbathing here), and see the great scenery that is all around us.

It’s also the cheapest option, we only paid 1 euro for our month pass, just enough money to make the commute not cost a lot of money, and that is coming from 2 women who would worry if they had to spend 5 euro on groceries without using coupons or discount cards.

Believe me, I love cows. But there is a certain satisfaction of riding a bike out in the country side. 🙂

I’m completely with you on this. For the most part I think the U.S. is way too car dependent, even here in Los Angeles where people tend to walk more due to all the great weather. Even affecting LA, the car culture has thrown me for a loop many times. For example, as I was working myself into a full blow sweat walking up the hill to a yoga class a few nights ago, I got thumbs up and honks for two guys in a Mercedes speeding along the mistaken belief that I was in a hurry.
